# ============================================================================
# UNIT 4 — DAYCOUNT (30/360 US accrued interest)
# ============================================================================

[2026-07-11] RESEARCH: 30/360 US day count verified against Wikipedia (Day count
    convention) / SIFMA. Ordered rules: (1) both D1,D2 last-day-of-Feb => D2=30;
    (2) D1 last-day-of-Feb => D1=30; (3) D2=31 and D1 in {30,31} => D2=30;
    (4) D1=31 => D1=30. Formula 360*(Y2-Y1)+30*(M2-M1)+(D2-D1). Key finding: the
    SIFMA/NASD bond basis (with the Feb rules) differs from Excel DAYS360
    (without them) by several days around Feb month-ends.

[2026-07-11] DECISION (Gap-H): Implement the NASD bond basis (US corporate-bond
    standard). Record the Excel DAYS360 count alongside in the baseline as audit
    evidence; 3/10 scenarios diverge (e.g. 28-Feb->31-Aug: NASD 180 vs Excel
    183 = $41.67 on $100k@5%). Equivalence test pins the NASD value AND the
    Rust-level day count so the divergence is a checked fact, not prose.

[2026-07-11] DECISION (Gap-I/J): Reproduce the rule order verbatim with Feb flags
    from original dates and rule 3's "30 or 31" clause (else 31-Jan->31-Mar = 61
    not 60). Leap rule y%4==0 && (y%100!=0 || y%400==0) (1900 not leap, 2000 is).

[2026-07-11] TDM RED: Wrote tests/day_equivalence.rs first, against a stub
    returning zeros. FAILED on feb_eom_nonleap NASD day count (0 vs 180).

