[2026-07-12] COMPILER EVIDENCE: Ran all six units through a live GnuCOBOL 3.1.2
    compiler (tests/compiler-derived/gnucobol-3.1.2). Five units + the seven
    same-scale CURRCVT rows matched the model baseline exactly. GnuCOBOL exposed
    ONE real COBOL-vs-model divergence: the CURRCVT COBOL as written stored its
    result in a fixed 2-dp field (WS-RESULT PIC S9(11)V99) and did NOT implement
    Gap-R (variable target minor unit). Raw COBOL: frf_to_itl 295182.43,
    dem_to_esp 21267.96, esp_to_itl 581860.75 — each a minor unit off the model's
    295182 / 21268 / 581861. The audit had flagged exactly this risk (Gap-R:
    "a port that hard-codes 2 dp mis-rounds every lira/peseta amount").

[2026-07-12] DECISION (Gap-R reconciliation): Correct the legacy COBOL to be
    regulation-compliant rather than propagate the defect. cobol/CURRCVT.cbl (and
    its normalized copy and the -RUN wrapper) now carry WS-MINOR-UNIT (0 for
    ITL/ESP, 2 otherwise, from the currency master) and round into a result field
    of the matching scale: WS-RESULT-0 PIC S9(13) for 0-dp targets, WS-RESULT-2
    PIC S9(11)V99 otherwise. This mirrors the model's minor(to) lookup. Rationale:
    SEMANTICS_CURR.md and EC 1103/97 make the 0-dp target minor unit mandatory;
    the fixed 2-dp field was a genuine legacy bug, and closing it in the COBOL
    (not just the Rust port) makes COBOL, model and Rust concordant. Historical
    trace preserved here and in RESULTS.md. Reversible: revert this commit to
    restore the fixed-2dp wrapper and the 3-row documented divergence.

[2026-07-12] VALIDATION: Regenerated CURRCVT-compiler-baseline.csv via the
    deterministic driver (tools/run_baselines.py generate). run_baselines.py
    verify = 1179 field comparisons, 0 mismatches vs live GnuCOBOL. check = 859
    comparisons, 0 unexpected mismatches, 0 divergences (Gap-R exception set now
    explicitly empty). Normalization invariant re-checked: canonical CURRCVT.cbl
    is character-identical (comments/whitespace/case stripped) to the normalized
    source. SHA256SUMS regenerated; sha256sum -c all OK.

